06:10.469 --> 06:11.669
<i>♪ The greenback boogie ♪</i>

06:14.533 --> 06:16.000
Break out the champagne,
Louis.

06:16.035 --> 06:16.968
That house in the Hamptons

06:17.003 --> 06:18.895
is gonna be yours
in 60 to 90 days.

06:19.017 --> 06:20.917
- They accepted my offer?
- That they did.

06:20.952 --> 06:23.586
Well, then I have something
much better than champagne...

06:23.622 --> 06:24.988
Wood.

06:25.023 --> 06:26.267
I don't really see how
that's better than champagne.

06:26.291 --> 06:27.624
Of course you don't.

06:27.659 --> 06:28.870
Because you don't know
that I'm having a replica

06:28.894 --> 06:30.193
of my house made for Tara,

06:30.228 --> 06:32.195
so she can see her
designs come to life.

06:32.230 --> 06:33.930
Louis, that's actually
really sweet.

06:33.965 --> 06:35.131
I know.

06:35.167 --> 06:38.935
Now, all I need to do
is pick the perfect wood.

06:39.446 --> 06:42.147
- I don't follow.
- Donna, the kind of wood you

06:42.182 --> 06:43.715
get says everything
you need to know

06:43.751 --> 06:45.183
about what kind of man you are.

06:45.484 --> 06:47.551
How hard or soft it is.

06:47.586 --> 06:50.053
How much it bends
when you're working it.

06:50.088 --> 06:51.488
How firm it is compared--

06:51.523 --> 06:53.568
- I got the picture, Louis.
- No, I don't think you do.

06:53.592 --> 06:54.758
Making Tara love my wood

06:54.793 --> 06:56.693
is the first step
toward making her love me.

06:56.817 --> 06:57.861
- Okay, Louis, calm down.
- No.

06:57.885 --> 06:59.162
I don't really want
to calm down,

06:59.186 --> 07:02.988
because all I can think
about my wood.

07:03.023 --> 07:05.958
So tell me, exactly how many
different kinds of wood

07:05.993 --> 07:08.182
have you sampled in your day?
All of them.

07:08.282 --> 07:10.282
Mahogany, chestnut, walnut,
all the nuts.

07:10.317 --> 07:11.416
Ebony?

07:11.451 --> 07:12.795
Don't even get me
started on ebony.

07:12.819 --> 07:14.230
When I see ebony, all I want to
do is put my hands all over it.

07:14.254 --> 07:15.365
- Oh, God.
- I want to live in it.

07:15.389 --> 07:17.066
I want to smack it
and hit it, rub it down.

07:17.090 --> 07:18.690
I just want to eat it.

07:18.725 --> 07:20.225
What's so funny?

07:20.260 --> 07:22.093
Nothing.
Um...

07:22.129 --> 07:26.731
I just think that
a man needs to follow his heart

07:26.767 --> 07:28.934
and choose the wood
that just feels right.

07:28.969 --> 07:30.502
- Feels right.
- Yeah.

07:30.537 --> 07:33.338
That's it.
Donna...

07:34.023 --> 07:35.367
I need you to help me
feel my wood.

07:35.391 --> 07:37.558
Oh, dear God.

07:37.894 --> 07:40.694
<i>[playful music]</i>

07:40.730 --> 07:42.062
God damn it, Julie,

07:42.098 --> 07:44.365
call his office again,
and this time tell him to find--

07:44.400 --> 07:46.600
If you're talking about
my office, there's no need.

07:46.636 --> 07:47.636
I'm right here.

07:47.670 --> 07:48.870
What the hell
took you so long?

07:48.905 --> 07:50.582
- I was unavailable.
- Well, I just got indicted,

07:50.606 --> 07:52.406
so from now on
you make yourself available.

07:52.441 --> 07:53.641
I get it.

07:53.676 --> 07:55.142
This all just got real
for you,

07:55.178 --> 07:58.412
so why don't you tell me right
now, how real is the rest of it?

07:58.969 --> 08:01.603
- What are you saying?
- I'm saying, Cahill claims

08:01.639 --> 08:02.883
that you can't make
the returns you do.

08:02.907 --> 08:04.973
You say you can, and I want
to know how you do it.

08:05.009 --> 08:07.176
We use a proprietary
trading algorithm.

08:07.211 --> 08:08.744
- Developed by who?
- My son-in-law.

08:08.779 --> 08:09.823
Good, then we can
give it to Cahill,

08:09.847 --> 08:10.991
'cause he just subpoenaed it.

08:11.015 --> 08:12.981
- No, we can't.
- Why the hell not?

08:13.195 --> 08:14.439
Because the trades
on which I make

08:14.463 --> 08:16.407
the most money have nothing
to do with that program.

08:16.431 --> 08:17.864
Are you kidding me?

08:17.900 --> 08:19.699
You're admitting
to inside trading?

08:19.735 --> 08:21.713
I'm not admitting to anything,
except that sometimes

08:21.737 --> 08:22.936
I trade with my gut.

08:22.971 --> 08:24.638
Well, I got news
for you, William.

08:24.673 --> 08:27.908
To a jury, that's gonna sound
like you're full of shit.

08:27.943 --> 08:31.444
Okay, smart guy,
pick up that journal.

08:31.864 --> 08:33.297
Give me a stock.

08:33.332 --> 08:35.176
NASDAQ, New York Stock Exchange,
I don't give a shit.

08:35.200 --> 08:37.601
Just pick one.

08:37.714 --> 08:39.481
- All right, Computech.
- Computech.

08:39.515 --> 08:41.683
1.59 billion shares
outstanding.

08:41.717 --> 08:43.650
Yesterday's close, 32, flat.

08:43.687 --> 08:45.320
Today's opening, 33 1/4.

08:45.355 --> 08:46.821
P/E's at 17.

08:46.857 --> 08:49.023
Earnings expected
to grow at 2% a year.

08:49.059 --> 08:50.203
What it doesn't say in there,

08:50.227 --> 08:51.471
is that the earnings
aren't gonna grow,

08:51.495 --> 08:53.194
because the CEO
doesn't give a shit,

08:53.230 --> 08:55.697
which makes it a value trap
dressed up like a princess,

08:55.732 --> 08:57.866
and I wouldn't touch it
with a ten-foot pole.

08:57.901 --> 08:59.278
That's a pretty
neat trick, William,

08:59.302 --> 09:01.469
but it isn't gonna stop
this subpoena.

09:01.505 --> 09:04.105
It's not a trick.
It's what I do.

09:04.141 --> 09:06.674
What you're gonna do,
is stop that son of a bitch

09:06.710 --> 09:08.743
from getting his hands
on my program.

09:09.279 --> 09:12.146
<i>[tense music]</i>

09:12.181 --> 09:14.282
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:14.317 --> 09:17.485
Rachel, whatever it is,
it's going to have to wait.

09:17.520 --> 09:18.998
Okay, but you told me
to bring you everything

09:19.022 --> 09:20.532
I have on the Bailey
case this morning.

09:20.556 --> 09:21.722
Great.
Leave it on my desk

09:21.758 --> 09:23.457
and I'll get to it
sometime this week.

09:23.493 --> 09:24.792
Oh, I'm sorry,
Jessica,

09:24.827 --> 09:26.105
I was really hoping
that we could go over it today.

09:26.129 --> 09:27.640
I was hoping to be out
the door by now.

09:27.664 --> 09:28.930
Look, I know that I said

09:28.965 --> 09:30.442
this wouldn't take up
too much of your time, but--

09:30.466 --> 09:33.634
Rachel, I said I would
do this, and I will,

09:33.670 --> 09:36.337
but you just have to be patient.
I understand.

09:36.372 --> 09:38.773
It's just, Leonard Bailey's
been patient for 12 years.

09:38.808 --> 09:41.042
And I have sympathy
for the man,

09:41.077 --> 09:44.478
but today's not the day.

09:44.514 --> 09:46.781
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

09:47.816 --> 09:50.817
[indistinct chatter]

09:52.487 --> 09:57.023
Don't bother with another menu.
I'll just have a Cobb salad.

09:57.059 --> 09:58.136
What do you think
you're doing?

09:58.160 --> 09:59.559
What does it look
like I'm doing?

09:59.594 --> 10:00.605
I'm having lunch with a client

10:00.629 --> 10:01.940
to discuss his
investment business.

10:01.964 --> 10:03.574
You don't represent
my investment business.

10:03.598 --> 10:05.043
Which is exactly why
we need to have lunch.

10:05.067 --> 10:06.466
No, we don't need
to have anything,

10:06.501 --> 10:08.479
'cause the deal was Harvey gets
me cleared of criminal charges,

10:08.503 --> 10:09.881
then you get the rest
of my business.

10:09.905 --> 10:11.282
I don't care what
the deal was, William.

10:11.306 --> 10:12.672
I care what the deal is.

10:12.898 --> 10:14.543
Because now that that
indictment's come down,

10:14.567 --> 10:17.901
Harvey is going to be
spending all of his time on you.

10:17.937 --> 10:21.338
That's not my problem.
I'm making it your problem.

10:21.374 --> 10:23.774
We get all of your business,
or we handle none of it.

10:23.809 --> 10:25.175
Bullshit.

10:25.211 --> 10:28.012
You quit, you lose billables
you can't afford to lose.

10:28.047 --> 10:29.713
We quit, and it looks like
we realized

10:29.749 --> 10:31.915
your case was a loser
and wanted distance from it,

10:32.288 --> 10:33.602
which you can't afford.

10:33.654 --> 10:36.789
You really want to start a
business relationship this way?

10:36.824 --> 10:39.158
I don't give a shit
how it starts, William.

10:39.193 --> 10:41.594
I give a shit how it looks.

10:41.629 --> 10:44.330
Oh, that's why you did
this here.

10:44.365 --> 10:46.932
You want it to look like you
already represent my firm.

10:46.968 --> 10:49.134
Well, look at that.

10:49.170 --> 10:51.770
Looks like I'm worth
hiring after all.

10:51.806 --> 10:54.006
So are we actually
going to talk business,

10:54.041 --> 10:56.508
or am I just gonna bill you
for the pleasure of my company?

10:56.544 --> 10:59.712
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

11:04.624 --> 11:08.292
Mike,
what can I do for you?

11:08.328 --> 11:11.129
You can tell me if you do
straight-up therapy or not.

11:11.164 --> 11:14.699
- What's on your mind?
- You didn't answer my question.

11:14.734 --> 11:15.933
I didn't think I needed to,

11:15.969 --> 11:17.480
since we've been doing
straight-up therapy

11:17.504 --> 11:18.936
since you got here.

11:19.464 --> 11:22.465
So, you want to tell me
what you're here for?

11:25.570 --> 11:29.405
My parents were killed
by a drunk driver when I was 11,

11:29.440 --> 11:31.107
and yesterday I found out that

11:31.142 --> 11:33.075
Kevin almost killed
someone drunk driving.

11:33.111 --> 11:35.077
So I need you to help me
act normal around him,

11:35.113 --> 11:37.313
so that I can get what I need,
so I can get out of here.

11:37.593 --> 11:39.759
Oh, well,
that's gonna be a problem.

11:39.795 --> 11:40.961
Because the goal of therapy

11:40.996 --> 11:43.330
is not to act normal,
it's to be normal.

11:43.365 --> 11:45.398
Yeah, well, I'll be normal
when I'm home

11:45.434 --> 11:46.845
with the woman I love
instead of dreaming

11:46.869 --> 11:49.202
that the guy I'm sharing a cell
with killed her.

11:49.238 --> 11:52.672
- What?
- I had a dream last night

11:52.708 --> 11:55.008
that I didn't have to inform
on Kevin anymore,

11:55.043 --> 11:57.878
because he killed Rachel
in an accident.

11:57.913 --> 11:59.557
And I must have been
talking about it in my sleep,

11:59.581 --> 12:01.314
because he asked me
about it today,

12:01.350 --> 12:04.784
so I told him the accident part,
and then we got in a fight.

12:04.820 --> 12:06.386
- Fight about what?
- I asked him

12:06.421 --> 12:08.755
if he even felt bad
about the guy he hit.

12:09.230 --> 12:10.897
So you turned it
back on him?

12:10.932 --> 12:12.276
What is that even
supposed to mean?

12:12.300 --> 12:14.300
It means that I think
you picked a fight with Kevin

12:14.336 --> 12:16.614
because you didn't want to think
about why you had that dream.

12:16.638 --> 12:18.071
I know why I had the dream.

12:18.106 --> 12:19.483
It's because he almost
killed someone

12:19.507 --> 12:20.851
the same way
my parents were killed.

12:20.875 --> 12:22.720
No, you had the dream,
because you don't want to deal

12:22.744 --> 12:24.155
with what you're doing
to your friend.

12:24.179 --> 12:27.013
- Oh, this again.
- Yes, this again.

12:27.048 --> 12:29.616
Mike, why do you think part of
the dream was finding out

12:29.651 --> 12:31.784
that you didn't have to inform
on him anymore?

12:31.820 --> 12:33.286
God damn it,
I did not come here

12:33.321 --> 12:34.921
to second guess my decision.

12:34.956 --> 12:36.623
Do you know what?
I don't care.

12:36.658 --> 12:38.591
Because I wouldn't be
doing my job,

12:38.627 --> 12:41.594
if I didn't inform you
that actions have consequences,

12:41.630 --> 12:42.829
and you seem to think that

12:42.864 --> 12:44.497
the only consequence
of what you're doing

12:44.532 --> 12:46.643
is getting out of here early,
but it's not.

12:46.743 --> 12:50.011
I think you don't know shit
about what I've been through.

12:50.046 --> 12:53.014
It's a mistake coming
to you for help.

12:56.529 --> 12:59.959
And this is the fifth bedroom,
and I'm completely open

12:59.960 --> 13:01.860
to you knocking down walls
or removing windows,

13:01.896 --> 13:04.596
by the way.
No, I love the windows.

13:04.632 --> 13:05.976
They let in so much light.
I agree.

13:06.000 --> 13:07.766
We should add a wall of glass.
What do

13:07.801 --> 13:09.401
I think the place
is beautiful,

13:09.436 --> 13:11.403
and I appreciate you bringing
these photos over,

13:11.438 --> 13:15.674
but when can we
go see it in person?

13:15.709 --> 13:18.107
- In person?
- Yes, of course.

13:18.108 --> 13:20.975
I need to see the space before
I can start drafting anything.

13:21.010 --> 13:22.877
I was just thinking we could
work closer together

13:22.878 --> 13:24.856
for the next 60 to 90 days
before you started that.

13:24.880 --> 13:26.625
- That wouldn't be productive.
- But I couldn't possibly

13:26.649 --> 13:28.593
make it out there in less than
seven to ten business days.

13:28.617 --> 13:29.783
That's too bad.

13:29.818 --> 13:31.563
I was gonna be out there
the day after tomorrow.

13:31.587 --> 13:32.831
I was thinking
we could see the space,

13:32.855 --> 13:34.287
and then maybe go have lunch.

13:34.323 --> 13:38.025
Lunch?
Together?

13:38.060 --> 13:40.927
Well, I wasn't thinking of
eating in separate restaurants.

13:40.963 --> 13:43.067
Ha!
Of course you weren't.

13:43.167 --> 13:44.499
Day after tomorrow's perfect.

13:44.535 --> 13:46.513
- But I thought you couldn't--
- I can, and I will,

13:46.537 --> 13:48.048
and I will meet you
at my ancestral home,

13:48.072 --> 13:50.272
that I've owned for quite
some time, day after tomorrow.

13:51.040 --> 13:53.908
<i>[tense music]</i>

13:53.943 --> 13:57.779
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:57.814 --> 13:59.747
Your Honor,
I'm simply requesting

13:59.783 --> 14:00.915
Mr. Sutter hand over--

14:00.950 --> 14:02.650
Something he has not right to.

14:02.685 --> 14:03.796
I have every right
to make sure

14:03.820 --> 14:05.720
that your client
is operating within the law.

14:05.755 --> 14:08.623
And what exactly is your basis
to say that he isn't?

14:08.932 --> 14:10.999
Your Honor, when you break
the home run record,

14:11.034 --> 14:12.901
and someone says,
"Your bat is corked,"

14:12.936 --> 14:14.369
you turn it over
to show it's not.

14:14.566 --> 14:18.101
Except when that bat is the
reason you hit all those homers,

14:18.136 --> 14:19.736
because the second he gets it,

14:19.771 --> 14:22.285
everyone in the world's
gonna know what's in it.

14:22.385 --> 14:25.820
And my client might as well
go out of business right now.

14:25.855 --> 14:27.421
That is
a ridiculous supposition

14:27.457 --> 14:29.256
without a shred of proof
to back it up.

14:29.292 --> 14:30.691
How's this for proof?

14:30.727 --> 14:33.085
Your Honor, six years ago,
Mr. Cahill

14:33.185 --> 14:35.686
went on a fishing expedition
just like this one.

14:35.721 --> 14:37.087
That has nothing to do
with this.

14:37.122 --> 14:38.188
Oh, doesn't it?

14:38.223 --> 14:40.357
He subpoenaed a proprietary
trading program

14:40.392 --> 14:41.591
from Kessler Capital.

14:41.627 --> 14:42.993
It proved no wrongdoing,

14:43.028 --> 14:44.868
and ten months later
they were out of business.

14:44.897 --> 14:46.530
That has nothing to do
with my subpoena.

14:46.565 --> 14:48.397
And I have an affidavit here

14:48.398 --> 14:50.799
from Mr. Kessler
saying it was directly

14:50.833 --> 14:52.299
because of your subpoena.

14:52.335 --> 14:54.702
Mr. Cahill,
is what he's saying true?

14:54.737 --> 14:56.537
Did you go after Kessler
in the same manner,

14:56.572 --> 14:58.872
and did he go
under ten months later?

14:58.908 --> 15:00.708
- Yes, but--
- No buts,

15:00.743 --> 15:02.176
do you have
any other evidence

15:02.211 --> 15:04.144
to present to the court?

15:04.180 --> 15:05.746
Not at this time, Your Honor.

15:05.781 --> 15:08.148
Then your request is denied.

15:08.184 --> 15:10.351
[bangs gavel]

15:10.386 --> 15:14.254
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:15.090 --> 15:16.330
Oh, there you are.
What the hell

15:16.358 --> 15:17.735
are you doing
in the executive kitchen?

15:17.759 --> 15:19.470
What does it look like
I'm doing? I'm being executive.

15:19.494 --> 15:20.660
But you're not an executive.

15:20.695 --> 15:23.730
Until I made the
executive decision that I was.

15:23.765 --> 15:25.798
Now, is there something
I can help you with?

15:25.834 --> 15:28.165
Yeah. I want you
to forget that latte

15:28.265 --> 15:30.399
and get me unfettered access
to my new home,

15:30.434 --> 15:31.444
after thoroughly cleansing it

15:31.468 --> 15:32.968
of any trace
of its former occupants.

15:33.003 --> 15:34.614
And why, exactly,
do you need me to do that?

15:34.638 --> 15:35.982
Because Tara wants
to see the house,

15:36.006 --> 15:37.894
and then have lunch
with me the day after tomorrow.

15:37.918 --> 15:39.818
Louis, your offer
was just accepted,

15:39.853 --> 15:40.919
and there's never been

15:40.955 --> 15:42.532
a one-day escrow
in the history of escrows.

15:42.556 --> 15:44.467
You don't think I know that?
I just spent the last hour

15:44.491 --> 15:46.136
arguing with five
different escrow officers.

15:46.160 --> 15:47.726
I get it.

15:47.761 --> 15:49.005
You want me to get people
to do things

15:49.029 --> 15:50.995
they'd never be willing to do,
in a timeframe

15:50.997 --> 15:52.441
that makes it impossible
for them to do it in.

15:52.465 --> 15:54.365
- Exactly.
- Then make me a double latte

15:54.400 --> 15:55.544
and get the hell out
of my way,

15:55.568 --> 15:57.012
because I'm about
to executive decision

15:57.036 --> 16:00.371
your sorry ass
into that house.

16:00.406 --> 16:02.273
What are you drinking?

16:02.308 --> 16:04.708
A 60-year-old bottle of the
finest single malt in the world.

16:04.744 --> 16:05.943
Then get me a glass.

16:05.978 --> 16:07.845
Not until I know
what happened in court today.

16:07.880 --> 16:09.480
Well, let me put it this way.

16:09.938 --> 16:11.338
The only thing
that Sean Cahill's

16:11.373 --> 16:12.373
gonna be drinking tonight

16:12.407 --> 16:14.307
is a shit-out-of-luck
daiquiri.

16:14.343 --> 16:15.942
- How'd you get it done?
- I established

16:15.978 --> 16:18.545
a pattern of him going fishing
without enough bait.

16:18.580 --> 16:20.158
Then have a drink
before you get back in there

16:20.182 --> 16:22.882
and knock the bastard out before
he can throw another punch.

16:23.340 --> 16:24.584
- What are you saying?
- I'm saying,

16:24.608 --> 16:28.176
I want you to get
this entire action dismissed.

16:28.211 --> 16:29.811
William,
that's a terrible idea.

16:29.846 --> 16:31.679
Not to me,
because he's got nothing.

16:31.715 --> 16:32.814
I don't care.

16:32.849 --> 16:35.050
What you're suggesting
is a mistake.

16:35.085 --> 16:36.446
You still haven't
told me why.

16:36.546 --> 16:38.312
Because you only get
one shot at dismissal,

16:38.348 --> 16:39.880
and now's not the time
to take it.

16:39.916 --> 16:41.715
Well, I say it is.
I'm not suggesting it.

16:41.751 --> 16:43.217
I'm flat out telling you
to do it.

16:43.252 --> 16:45.619
I didn't get where I am
by letting my clients bully me.

16:45.655 --> 16:46.620
And I didn't get
where I am

16:46.656 --> 16:49.223
by allowing my employees
to dictate terms,

16:49.258 --> 16:51.759
which I already did once today.
I'm not gonna do it again.

16:51.793 --> 16:53.938
- What's that supposed to mean?
- It means Jessica Pearson

16:53.962 --> 16:55.228
convinced me
to give your firm

16:55.263 --> 16:56.796
the rest of my business
this afternoon.

16:56.831 --> 16:58.943
So if you don't move to have the
charges against me dismissed,

16:58.967 --> 17:01.334
I'll have her do it for you.

17:01.369 --> 17:04.337
<i>[tense music]</i>

17:04.372 --> 17:10.609
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:11.012 --> 17:12.479
Harvey, I was just
on my way out.

17:12.515 --> 17:14.114
Well, you can be
on your way back in,

17:14.150 --> 17:15.549
because I just came
from Sutter's.

17:15.584 --> 17:17.865
I take it he told you about
our little conversation today.

17:17.906 --> 17:20.406
If, by conversation,
you mean going behind my back

17:20.442 --> 17:21.875
and getting his
investment business,

17:21.910 --> 17:23.242
then yeah, he told me.

17:23.278 --> 17:24.944
I didn't go behind your back.

17:24.980 --> 17:26.546
I saw an opportunity,
and I took it.

17:26.580 --> 17:29.616
Well, now he's seeing an
opportunity, and he's taking it.

17:29.651 --> 17:32.052
- What are you talking about?
- He's leveraging what you did

17:32.087 --> 17:35.055
to get me to move
for an immediate dismissal.

17:35.091 --> 17:37.236
And, don't tell me,
you think it's gonna work?

17:37.238 --> 17:38.337
I sure as hell do.

17:38.373 --> 17:40.339
And the second it does,
Mike's chance

17:40.375 --> 17:42.709
at getting out goes with it,
thanks to you.

17:42.744 --> 17:44.877
Hang on there, tiger.

17:44.913 --> 17:47.346
You're not in this position
because of something I did.

17:47.362 --> 17:49.028
You're in it
because of Sutter,

17:49.063 --> 17:51.130
and he'd be demanding
you have this case dismissed

17:51.165 --> 17:52.865
whether we have his
other business or not.

17:52.900 --> 17:55.368
- Oh, that's not the point.
- No, Harvey, the point is,

17:55.403 --> 17:56.969
I have been out there
busting my ass

17:57.005 --> 17:59.672
trying to find us
new business for days,

17:59.707 --> 18:01.443
and do you know
what they keep asking?

18:01.543 --> 18:03.609
Why don't we have
Sutter's investment business.

18:03.645 --> 18:05.912
Goddamn right.
We needed it.

18:05.947 --> 18:09.949
I got it, and now
they're not asking anymore.

18:10.368 --> 18:12.469
Well, what's gonna happen
when we lose this case,

18:12.504 --> 18:13.837
and his business goes away?

18:13.872 --> 18:17.073
What happens is, we're already
built back up by then,

18:17.109 --> 18:18.842
so instead of blaming me

18:18.877 --> 18:20.677
for the position Sutter
has put you in,

18:20.712 --> 18:21.878
I suggest you go ahead

18:21.913 --> 18:24.547
and find yourself
a way out of it.

18:24.583 --> 18:29.986
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:30.366 --> 18:32.567
Rachel,
what can I do for you?

18:32.602 --> 18:35.236
I was hoping you could
do something for Leonard Bailey.

18:35.271 --> 18:37.405
I drafted a motion
to reopen his case,

18:37.440 --> 18:39.440
but I need a current member
of the Bar to file it.

18:39.810 --> 18:40.887
And what happened
to the person

18:40.911 --> 18:42.210
you said
was gonna take this on?

18:42.245 --> 18:43.589
She can't get to it
till later this week,

18:43.613 --> 18:45.260
but I want to get on this
as soon as possible.

18:45.284 --> 18:46.884
Rachel, I'm sorry,
but I told you before,

18:46.919 --> 18:49.085
I don't have the resources
to work on this case now.

18:49.087 --> 18:50.898
Professor, this man has a wife
who gave up on him

18:50.922 --> 18:53.456
and children
that he doesn't see.

18:53.543 --> 18:55.777
His entire life
is passing him by,

18:55.812 --> 18:58.379
and the only way for him
to start getting it back

18:58.415 --> 19:01.583
is to just have someone
who cares enough about him

19:01.618 --> 19:06.588
that they give him
a half hour of their time.

19:07.023 --> 19:09.957
Let me see your motion.

19:16.432 --> 19:19.700
[exhales sharply]
This is well drafted.

19:19.736 --> 19:21.135
Thank you.

19:21.745 --> 19:24.413
But I'm afraid it won't work.

19:24.448 --> 19:25.814
What are you talking--no--

19:25.850 --> 19:27.427
look, there's no reason that
he should have been convicted.

19:27.451 --> 19:29.262
Look at the evidence.
That's not the point, Rachel.

19:29.286 --> 19:31.486
I've worked on dozens
of these cases,

19:31.522 --> 19:33.133
and like it or not,
the standard to reopen

19:33.157 --> 19:34.823
is higher than what it says
in the books.

19:34.859 --> 19:38.393
You need something undeniable.

19:38.429 --> 19:39.928
Then what am I supposed to do?

19:39.964 --> 19:43.298
You're supposed to use your
gumption to find that something,

19:43.334 --> 19:45.834
and get Leonard Bailey the
justice he's been waiting for.

19:50.412 --> 19:52.979
Harvey, it's late.
Whatever you're doing here

19:53.015 --> 19:54.392
is gonna have to wait
until morning.

19:54.416 --> 19:56.383
- It can't.
- Why's that?

19:56.418 --> 19:58.885
Because Sutter wants me to
move for an immediate dismissal.

19:58.920 --> 20:00.120
What?

20:00.155 --> 20:01.432
You leveraged me
into bringing this indictment,

20:01.456 --> 20:02.656
and now you want to toss it?

20:02.691 --> 20:05.091
I don't want to toss it,
but if I don't,

20:05.127 --> 20:06.860
he's gonna find
someone else who will.

20:06.895 --> 20:08.461
What are you
doing here, Harvey?

20:08.497 --> 20:10.630
Nothing, I'm just finishing
my dinner.

20:11.381 --> 20:13.214
The thing is,
I don't like to litter,

20:13.249 --> 20:14.482
so why don't you
do me a favor?

20:14.517 --> 20:18.986
If I forget this when I go,

20:19.022 --> 20:21.055
why don't you take it upstairs
and throw it away?

20:21.090 --> 20:22.656
What's in the bag, Harvey?

20:22.692 --> 20:25.259
A wrapper, couple napkins,

20:25.294 --> 20:26.494
and a few extra fries.

20:26.529 --> 20:28.362
What the hell is
in the bag, Harvey?

20:28.398 --> 20:29.964
What you needed to keep
this case going,

20:29.999 --> 20:31.199
and I stopped you
from getting.

20:31.234 --> 20:32.778
Damn it, you said
you were gonna defend him

20:32.802 --> 20:35.002
to the best of your ability.
And I meant it.

20:35.038 --> 20:37.338
But I also knew,
if push came to shove,

20:37.373 --> 20:39.907
I'd do what
I had to to get Mike out,

20:39.942 --> 20:41.308
and I made my peace with it.

20:41.344 --> 20:43.010
- Yeah, well, I haven't.
- Yes, you have.

20:43.046 --> 20:44.857
- What are you talking about?
- You've been giving me

20:44.881 --> 20:47.782
this song and dance
about not colluding,

20:47.817 --> 20:49.950
and it didn't matter
what I said back to you,

20:49.986 --> 20:53.054
as long as it was something
to let you believe we wouldn't.

20:53.089 --> 20:56.023
Because that song wasn't for me,
it was for you.

20:56.059 --> 20:58.559
- Oh, for me? Bullshit.
- I don't think so, Sean,

20:58.594 --> 20:59.860
because you don't break a guy

20:59.896 --> 21:03.264
out of prison
just to advance your career.

21:03.299 --> 21:06.167
Look, this means something
to you.

21:06.202 --> 21:07.413
I don't need to know
what it is,

21:07.437 --> 21:08.969
but it means something
to me too,

21:09.005 --> 21:11.072
so let's just admit
that we're in this together

21:11.107 --> 21:13.374
and get this thing done.

21:13.409 --> 21:16.243
Take that garbage
and throw it away.

21:16.279 --> 21:20.281
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:26.477 --> 21:28.978
Now can I have champagne?

21:29.013 --> 21:30.724
You got the realtor to
give you the key to the house.

21:30.748 --> 21:33.015
Not only that, I got him
to agree to take the Kellmans

21:33.051 --> 21:34.550
to brunch tomorrow
from 10:00 to 2:00

21:34.586 --> 21:36.185
to celebrate their big sale.

21:36.617 --> 21:37.816
Well, that is great,
Donna,

21:37.851 --> 21:39.195
but I don't just need
to get into the house.

21:39.219 --> 21:41.586
I need Tara to believe that
it's my house, which means--

21:41.622 --> 21:43.633
No lock box on the door,
no for sale sign in the yard,

21:43.657 --> 21:45.201
and no personal
belongings in the house,

21:45.225 --> 21:47.626
which is why we are
gonna be there at 10:01

21:47.661 --> 21:49.194
to stage the shit
out of that place.

21:49.382 --> 21:52.283
Oh, and these
are coming with us.

21:54.821 --> 21:56.788
You reframed pictures
of Bruno?

21:57.201 --> 21:59.001
In the style of the house.

21:59.036 --> 22:03.238
And not just Bruno...

22:03.274 --> 22:05.307
Mikado.

22:05.696 --> 22:07.363
That's perfect, Donna.

22:07.398 --> 22:09.098
I just thought showing Tara
your wood

22:09.133 --> 22:11.801
wasn't the only way to show her
what kind of man you are.

22:11.836 --> 22:12.968
Thank you, Donna.

22:13.004 --> 22:14.837
You're welcome, Louis.

22:19.421 --> 22:20.687
Since when do we get a room

22:20.722 --> 22:23.356
instead of having to use
those damn phones?

22:23.391 --> 22:27.193
Since I officially
became part of your legal team.

22:27.228 --> 22:28.561
- My legal team?
- That's right.

22:28.596 --> 22:31.230
The firm that I work for
is taking your case.

22:35.512 --> 22:39.347
After all this time.

22:39.382 --> 22:41.983
Thank you.

22:42.018 --> 22:44.552
You're welcome.

22:44.588 --> 22:46.988
But we still need
to get the case reopened,

22:47.023 --> 22:50.425
and to do that we need
to find something new.

22:50.460 --> 22:51.968
So where do we get that?

22:52.068 --> 22:53.612
I was going through
the state's case file,

22:53.636 --> 22:55.403
and I read your police report.

22:55.438 --> 22:57.371
You said there was a woman
with you that night

22:57.407 --> 23:00.620
who can testify that you didn't
kill that couple.

23:00.720 --> 23:04.555
That's right, Maria,
but that's not new.

23:04.590 --> 23:06.430
Well, it's new as far
as the court's concerned,

23:06.459 --> 23:08.730
because it was never
admitted at trial.

23:08.830 --> 23:10.897
- Well, let's admit it.
- It's not that easy.

23:10.932 --> 23:12.710
I need to understand
why it was never admitted.

23:12.734 --> 23:16.770
Because the damn woman up
and disappeared before my trial.

23:16.805 --> 23:18.471
My lawyer didn't do a thing.

23:18.507 --> 23:20.073
You had an alibi witness,

23:20.108 --> 23:21.748
and your public defender
let her get away.

23:21.777 --> 23:23.076
That's what I've been saying.

23:23.111 --> 23:25.178
Maria could have told the jury
that I didn't do it,

23:25.213 --> 23:26.746
instead no one told them.

23:26.782 --> 23:29.315
Two weeks later,
I'm in here,

23:29.351 --> 23:31.518
and I've been here
ever since.

23:31.553 --> 23:35.522
Is there anything else
I need to know?

23:35.890 --> 23:38.724
Then I need to find
Maria Gomez.

23:46.200 --> 23:48.801
Look, man, please,
I really don't want to talk.

23:48.836 --> 23:51.337
Good, 'cause
I want you to listen.

23:54.876 --> 23:59.211
When I was a kid,
I thought we had it good.

23:59.247 --> 24:01.847
And we did. Had a nice house,
nice neighborhood.

24:02.347 --> 24:05.081
Except for one thing.

24:05.116 --> 24:08.217
Turns out my father...

24:08.253 --> 24:09.886
was a criminal.

24:10.050 --> 24:12.117
One day he got caught.
He went to prison.

24:12.153 --> 24:14.353
My whole life fell apart.

24:14.389 --> 24:16.989
How old were you?

24:17.025 --> 24:19.458
15.

24:19.494 --> 24:21.260
I'll tell you something.

24:21.295 --> 24:24.330
I hated that man for doing
what he did to me,

24:24.365 --> 24:27.633
so I did what messed up
15-year-olds do.

24:27.668 --> 24:31.137
- Started acting out.
- Acting out?

24:31.887 --> 24:37.057
Brother, I was on my way
to a place worse than this.

24:37.092 --> 24:39.392
Finally, my mom made me
see someone,

24:39.428 --> 24:41.595
and he helped me realize

24:41.630 --> 24:45.499
that if I didn't change,
I was gonna ruin my life.

24:45.534 --> 24:48.201
So I straightened out
and turned my life around.

24:48.663 --> 24:50.663
And that's why you do
what you do.

24:50.698 --> 24:54.033
Yeah.

24:54.068 --> 24:56.068
- Why are you telling me this?
- Because the way

24:56.103 --> 24:59.772
that man got through to me
was to open up about himself,

24:59.807 --> 25:03.209
and I realized that if
I really want to help you,

25:03.244 --> 25:05.644
I got to do the same.

25:05.680 --> 25:08.581
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:08.616 --> 25:12.384
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:12.876 --> 25:14.742
All right, I dragged this out
as long as I can,

25:14.778 --> 25:16.422
but I'm pretty much done
drafting this motion.

25:16.446 --> 25:17.712
So I'll need you to proof it--

25:17.747 --> 25:18.824
Harvey, before I do that,
I think you should take

25:18.848 --> 25:20.381
a look at these.

25:20.614 --> 25:22.513
- What is it?
- Cahill issued subpoenas

25:22.549 --> 25:24.682
to deposition William Sutter
and Kevin Miller.

25:24.718 --> 25:27.518
- That sneaky son of a bitch.
- Why are you smiling?

25:27.554 --> 25:28.953
Because last night
I went to Cahill

25:28.989 --> 25:31.823
and tried to give him
Sutter's trading program.

25:32.057 --> 25:33.623
- You did what?
- It was the only way

25:33.659 --> 25:35.992
I could see to stop the case
from getting dismissed,

25:36.028 --> 25:37.094
but he wouldn't take it.

25:37.642 --> 25:39.108
And this buys you time.

25:39.143 --> 25:41.377
It does, if the judge
waits to rule on our motion

25:41.412 --> 25:44.046
until after Cahill conducts
these depositions.

25:44.082 --> 25:46.160
Harvey, even if that works,
what if Cahill doesn't get

25:46.184 --> 25:48.162
enough from the depositions
to keep the case alive?

25:48.186 --> 25:50.064
Then Mike's chance of getting
out of prison is gone,

25:50.088 --> 25:51.721
which means Cahill's
not the only one

25:51.756 --> 25:54.924
that needs to use this
to try and get something.

25:57.838 --> 25:59.504
I have to admit, Ms. Zane,
when you said

25:59.566 --> 26:01.778
you were looking into the Bailey
case, my interest was piqued.

26:01.802 --> 26:04.002
That was a long time ago.

26:04.037 --> 26:05.482
Well, you've obviously
come a long way

26:05.506 --> 26:07.272
since your public defender days.

26:07.307 --> 26:10.408
You don't exactly see the best
of humanity at that job,

26:10.444 --> 26:12.911
which makes it one
you can only do for so long.

26:12.946 --> 26:15.247
But you didn't come here
to be my therapist.

26:15.282 --> 26:18.316
No, I came to talk
about Maria Gomez.

26:18.352 --> 26:19.551
What about her?

26:19.586 --> 26:21.620
I'm curious as to how you
can have an alibi witness

26:21.655 --> 26:22.621
on a murder case,

26:22.656 --> 26:24.096
and your client ends up
on death row.

26:24.203 --> 26:26.103
Because I didn't have
an alibi witness.

26:26.138 --> 26:27.971
I had a no-show
who vanished into thin air,

26:28.007 --> 26:30.150
and I didn't have the resources
to find her.

26:30.250 --> 26:32.250
And you didn't think
to ask the police at trial

26:32.285 --> 26:34.252
why they didn't follow up
on Leonard's alibi?

26:34.287 --> 26:35.386
I did think of it,

26:35.422 --> 26:36.966
and they would have said
what they always say,

26:36.990 --> 26:39.101
"Every murderer claims
to have an alibi,"

26:39.201 --> 26:41.235
and if I couldn't produce her,
why should they?

26:41.270 --> 26:42.814
Well, you could have
at least asked for postponement,

26:42.838 --> 26:44.071
to have time to find her.

26:44.106 --> 26:45.739
And I would have,
except for one thing.

26:45.774 --> 26:48.075
I wasn't sure a drug addict
with a prior conviction

26:48.110 --> 26:50.310
would have done
Leonard Bailey much good.

26:50.722 --> 26:52.855
That's about her character,
not the facts of the case.

26:52.890 --> 26:55.224
Her character is
a fact of the case,

26:55.259 --> 26:56.670
and when I pressed her
as to what the two of them

26:56.694 --> 26:58.105
were doing at the time
of those murders,

26:58.129 --> 27:00.096
she admitted they were
both on meth,

27:00.131 --> 27:01.564
and it wasn't the first time.

27:01.599 --> 27:03.599
Which, by the way,
might have something to do with

27:03.635 --> 27:06.068
why she never
showed up at trial.

27:06.549 --> 27:09.450
So you can try to reopen
this case if you want, Ms. Zane,

27:09.485 --> 27:13.854
but I am telling you,
you're wasting your time.

27:13.889 --> 27:19.526
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:19.755 --> 27:21.755
What's going on?

27:21.790 --> 27:24.357
What's going on is,
the clock's ticking.

27:24.393 --> 27:26.993
Sutter wants me
to get the case dismissed.

27:27.029 --> 27:28.795
- What? If that happens, I'll--
- I know.

27:28.830 --> 27:30.030
Now, listen to me.

27:30.065 --> 27:31.865
I bought us a little time,

27:31.900 --> 27:34.401
but I need you to do something.

27:34.436 --> 27:37.470
Okay.

27:37.506 --> 27:39.639
What is it?
Sutter doesn't know this yet,

27:39.675 --> 27:41.085
but he and I are gonna
be here tomorrow

27:41.109 --> 27:43.243
to have a practice deposition
with Kevin.

27:43.465 --> 27:45.398
So I need you to do the best

27:45.434 --> 27:47.767
Sean Cahill
you have to get them talking.

27:47.803 --> 27:50.670
You want me in the room?

27:50.706 --> 27:52.105
I don't think
that's a good idea.

27:52.140 --> 27:53.751
Didn't you hear me?
We're running out of time.

27:53.775 --> 27:55.420
I heard you, but I don't think
it's a good idea

27:55.444 --> 27:57.744
for me to be in the same room
as Kevin right now.

27:57.779 --> 28:00.447
- The drunk driving.
- You knew?

28:00.482 --> 28:02.449
- I just found out.
- Well, then you also know

28:02.484 --> 28:04.800
it's probably not the best time
for me to chum up to him.

28:04.900 --> 28:06.466
I'm not asking you
to chum up to him.

28:06.502 --> 28:08.735
I'm asking you
to piss him off.

28:08.771 --> 28:11.638
- What are you talking about?
- Kevin knows something,

28:11.673 --> 28:13.240
and he's not talking.

28:13.275 --> 28:15.709
So we could sit around here
for the next two years

28:15.744 --> 28:18.011
waiting for him to tell you,
or we can light a fire

28:18.046 --> 28:19.412
under his ass
by reminding him

28:19.448 --> 28:20.881
that Sutter's out there,

28:20.916 --> 28:23.016
while he's in here.

28:23.051 --> 28:27.420
Now, are you with me or not?

28:27.456 --> 28:28.456
I'm with you.

28:34.910 --> 28:37.345
I take it you're here
to give me the good news.

28:37.380 --> 28:40.348
- I'm afraid not.
- I thought I made myself clear.

28:40.383 --> 28:41.815
If you don't make a motion
to dismiss this--

28:41.816 --> 28:43.432
I did file a motion
to dismiss,

28:43.532 --> 28:44.464
but it doesn't matter,

28:44.500 --> 28:46.333
because Cahill filed subpoenas

28:46.368 --> 28:48.401
to depose you
and your son-in-law first,

28:48.437 --> 28:50.637
and until those
depositions happen,

28:50.672 --> 28:52.355
the court won't file
on the motion.

28:52.391 --> 28:53.490
Goddamn it.

28:53.525 --> 28:54.669
How the hell did he know
to do that

28:54.693 --> 28:56.237
when we're about to have
the case thrown out?

28:56.261 --> 28:59.229
I don't know, but that's not
what I came here to talk about,

28:59.316 --> 29:01.349
because we need to get you
and Kevin Miller

29:01.385 --> 29:03.885
in a room to prepare you
for your deposition.

29:03.921 --> 29:06.099
- You want us to go to prison?
- I don't see any other choice,

29:06.123 --> 29:08.368
so you should call whoever it is
you were gonna meet this morning

29:08.392 --> 29:09.469
and tell them
you can't make it,

29:09.493 --> 29:12.360
because you and I
are going to Danbury.

29:12.396 --> 29:15.297
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

29:15.332 --> 29:22.737
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:23.063 --> 29:25.230
Were you really serious
about wanting to help me?

29:25.265 --> 29:28.733
Why do I get the feeling
that's not a simple question?

29:28.768 --> 29:31.135
Because I want to know if
you're willing to give me access

29:31.171 --> 29:33.304
to certain records.

29:33.890 --> 29:36.857
I'm sorry, Mike, I cannot give
information on other inmates.

29:36.893 --> 29:38.370
Oh, that's okay, because those
aren't the records

29:38.394 --> 29:41.328
I'm looking for.

29:41.364 --> 29:44.131
Did you find Maria?

29:44.167 --> 29:48.135
You know, I haven't even
started looking for her yet,

29:48.171 --> 29:50.004
because you lied to me.

29:50.741 --> 29:53.742
What?

29:53.777 --> 29:56.078
I didn't lie to you
about shit.

29:56.113 --> 29:58.247
Well, you certainly didn't
tell me that you and Maria

29:58.282 --> 30:01.016
were high the night
of those murders.

30:01.051 --> 30:03.719
- Who told you that?
- Georgina Casey.

30:04.062 --> 30:05.328
You went to see my old lawyer?

30:05.363 --> 30:08.832
Yes, I did.

30:08.867 --> 30:11.367
And now you sitting over there
looking at me like,

30:11.765 --> 30:15.466
"You know, maybe he could have
killed those people after all."

30:15.502 --> 30:18.169
Leonard, when I went into that
meeting, I was on your side.

30:18.205 --> 30:20.585
And you came out of it
off it.

30:20.685 --> 30:22.852
No, when I came out of it,
I had questions.

30:22.887 --> 30:25.621
Okay, ask them.
I got nothing to hide.

30:25.656 --> 30:28.624
Really? Because you hid
something from me the last time.

30:28.659 --> 30:29.792
That was different.

30:29.827 --> 30:31.691
- No, it's relevant.
- No, it isn't.

30:31.791 --> 30:33.925
You were high the night
of the murders,

30:33.960 --> 30:35.426
and you lied to me about it.

30:35.461 --> 30:38.629
Because I'm ashamed of
how I used to be.

30:38.665 --> 30:42.066
I was a high school dropout
on my way nowhere,

30:42.101 --> 30:46.704
so, yeah, I looked for an escape
when I could afford one.

30:46.938 --> 30:48.905
I'm not saying
I didn't make some mistakes

30:48.940 --> 30:50.874
or maybe even commit
a few crimes,

30:50.909 --> 30:55.645
but killing those kids
was not one of them.

30:55.680 --> 30:57.380
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:57.893 --> 31:01.427
And that's the truth,
but I guess it doesn't matter,

31:01.463 --> 31:03.263
because if you don't
find Maria,

31:03.298 --> 31:06.199
someday they're gonna walk me
down that hall

31:06.234 --> 31:07.901
and put me to death.

31:07.936 --> 31:10.637
Then I guess I better
get back to finding her.

31:10.672 --> 31:13.973
But, Leonard,
I'm telling you,

31:14.462 --> 31:17.429
if you're not straight
with me,

31:17.465 --> 31:19.398
this isn't gonna work.

31:19.433 --> 31:23.602
Then I won't ever leave
anything out again.

31:26.589 --> 31:28.856
This is ridiculous.
This kid's no Sean Cahill.

31:28.891 --> 31:31.759
This kid made Sean Cahill
look like a fool

31:31.794 --> 31:33.361
without even having
a law degree.

31:33.396 --> 31:35.822
Just so you know, when
you attack opposing counsel,

31:35.922 --> 31:37.033
it kind of makes
you look afraid.

31:37.057 --> 31:40.258
[scoffs]
I'm not afraid of you.

31:40.293 --> 31:42.894
Okay, then why don't you
tell me this,

31:42.929 --> 31:45.630
what's the best thing
about having so much money?

31:45.665 --> 31:47.198
- What?
- You heard me.

31:47.233 --> 31:48.733
You got the penthouse
in Manhattan.

31:48.768 --> 31:51.102
You got the villa in the south
of France. You get two yachts--

31:51.121 --> 31:53.354
- So what?
- So what?

31:53.390 --> 31:54.667
So I wouldn't want
to give all of that up.

31:54.691 --> 31:56.491
Would you, Mr. Miller?

31:56.526 --> 31:58.359
- Me?
- Yeah, you.

31:58.395 --> 32:01.626
I mean, you had use
of all of these places too,

32:01.628 --> 32:03.728
until you threw it
all away driving drunk, that is.

32:03.763 --> 32:05.096
- What?
- Objection.

32:05.131 --> 32:06.698
Irrelevant.
I think it's very relevant.

32:06.733 --> 32:08.666
For all I know,
Kevin could be somehow involved.

32:08.702 --> 32:10.257
- That's insane.
- That's insane?

32:10.357 --> 32:12.101
You're the developer
of the trading software.

32:12.125 --> 32:13.636
And I'm not the one
who's on trial here.

32:13.660 --> 32:16.061
Then let's talk about
the one who is.

32:16.096 --> 32:17.974
How do you feel about the fact
that your father-in-law

32:17.998 --> 32:19.898
never came to visit
you in prison?

32:19.933 --> 32:21.666
- Excuse me?
- You heard me.

32:21.702 --> 32:24.013
He hasn't come to see you once.
How does that make you feel?

32:24.037 --> 32:26.771
- It doesn't matter to me.
- [chuckles]

32:27.391 --> 32:30.125
He could be lying on a beach
in the French Riviera,

32:30.160 --> 32:31.538
while you can barely see
your wife and kids,

32:31.562 --> 32:32.705
and that doesn't matter to you?

32:32.729 --> 32:34.663
Mr. Miller's family
has nothing to do

32:34.698 --> 32:35.809
with this investigation.
Mr. Miller's family

32:35.833 --> 32:37.732
is the subject
of this investigation,

32:37.768 --> 32:39.279
and his father in law
clearly doesn't give a shit--

32:39.303 --> 32:40.780
I'm grateful for everything
Kevin's done for me,

32:40.804 --> 32:43.405
and he knows it.
Yeah, right.

32:43.440 --> 32:45.106
I'm sorry, what was that?

32:45.142 --> 32:46.986
Are you disputing the fact
that he's grateful to you?

32:47.010 --> 32:48.343
I'm not answering
that question.

32:48.378 --> 32:49.578
This isn't
getting us anywhere.

32:49.613 --> 32:50.924
He's getting
you ready for Cahill.

32:50.948 --> 32:52.425
I wouldn't have
to get ready for Cahill

32:52.449 --> 32:55.106
if you did your goddamn job
and got this case dismissed.

32:55.206 --> 32:56.371
That's right,
get someone else

32:56.407 --> 32:58.007
to cover up your mess
like you always do.

32:58.042 --> 32:59.007
You got something you want
to say to me?

32:59.043 --> 33:00.253
I got something I want
to do to you.

33:00.277 --> 33:01.421
You better remember
who you're talking to.

33:01.445 --> 33:02.656
I know exactly
who I'm talking to,

33:02.680 --> 33:03.757
the guy who doesn't
give a shit

33:03.781 --> 33:04.791
about anyone else
other than himself.

33:04.815 --> 33:06.515
- That's enough.
- That is enough.

33:06.550 --> 33:07.716
This is your trial.

33:07.751 --> 33:09.129
It's not mine,
and I'm done with this,

33:09.153 --> 33:11.553
and I'm done with you!

33:11.589 --> 33:13.055
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:13.090 --> 33:15.591
Guard.
[bangs on door]

33:15.626 --> 33:23.298
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:23.334 --> 33:25.100
[bangs on table]
Son of a bitch.

33:25.665 --> 33:26.976
I knew that kid
would be a problem.

33:27.000 --> 33:29.467
Relax. That's the whole reason
I wanted Mike in here.

33:29.503 --> 33:30.902
If Kevin gets
any funny ideas,

33:30.937 --> 33:34.005
Mike's gonna calm him down
and let us know.

33:34.040 --> 33:37.342
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:37.877 --> 33:40.811
[indistinct chatter]

33:46.786 --> 33:48.797
You guys really get under
each other's skin, don't you?

33:48.821 --> 33:50.121
You have no idea
how many times

33:50.156 --> 33:52.690
I thought about punching
that bastard in his smug face.

33:52.725 --> 33:56.127
I'm guessing he's thought
about punching you too.

33:56.162 --> 33:57.862
What the hell is that
supposed to mean?

33:58.258 --> 34:00.725
It means his daughter
married a criminal.

34:00.761 --> 34:02.271
He's got to live with that.
You know what?

34:02.295 --> 34:03.373
I've had just about enough
of you

34:03.397 --> 34:04.963
giving me shit
for what I did.

34:04.998 --> 34:06.109
Well, maybe I'll stop
giving you shit

34:06.133 --> 34:07.432
when your story starts
adding up.

34:07.467 --> 34:08.667
Excuse me?

34:08.702 --> 34:09.812
You said you got three years
for drunk driving,

34:09.835 --> 34:10.835
but you got no priors,

34:10.871 --> 34:12.270
and this guy
made a full recovery.

34:12.304 --> 34:14.906
99 times out of 100, that means
you're getting probation.

34:14.940 --> 34:16.518
Then I guess
I had shitty representation.

34:16.543 --> 34:17.809
Bullshit.

34:17.844 --> 34:18.920
Money like yours doesn't
buy shitty representation.

34:18.945 --> 34:20.289
Then I don't know
what to tell you.

34:20.313 --> 34:22.433
How about you start with
telling me the goddamn truth?

34:23.065 --> 34:24.277
You want to know the truth?
I'll tell you,

34:24.301 --> 34:27.568
because I'm sick
of holding it in, man.

34:27.603 --> 34:30.237
I got three years, because when
they offered me a deal

34:30.281 --> 34:32.248
to turn on him,
I said no.

34:32.283 --> 34:33.860
You had to turn them down.
He didn't do it.

34:33.885 --> 34:35.217
No, I had to turn them down,

34:35.253 --> 34:39.054
because he's not
the only one involved.

34:39.242 --> 34:41.208
What?

34:44.280 --> 34:47.248
You asked me why
I was drinking that night.

34:47.283 --> 34:49.527
It was because I found out the
thing that I worked so hard on

34:49.552 --> 34:52.585
to get that prick's approval
was nothing but a lie.

34:52.621 --> 34:55.822
- Your trading program.
- Yeah, my program.

34:55.858 --> 34:57.169
Turns out he wasn't
using it at all.

34:57.193 --> 35:00.127
He was just
insider trading the whole time.

35:00.163 --> 35:03.264
Okay, so you got home,
you told Jill,

35:03.299 --> 35:05.700
and she didn't believe you.

35:05.735 --> 35:08.135
No, Mike.

35:08.171 --> 35:11.272
She not only believed me,
she...

35:11.307 --> 35:13.307
she already knew.

35:13.342 --> 35:15.242
[exhales sharply]
She was in on it.

35:15.278 --> 35:16.610
Yeah.

35:16.646 --> 35:19.480
So I went out,
and I got drunk.

35:19.515 --> 35:20.815
And the next thing
I knew,

35:20.850 --> 35:23.551
I had to choose between
going to prison for three years,

35:23.586 --> 35:29.023
or the mother of my children
going away for a whole lot more.

35:29.058 --> 35:31.726
- Kevin, you got--
- No.

35:31.761 --> 35:36.097
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:40.492 --> 35:42.760
Okay, I have removed

35:42.796 --> 35:45.329
every possible trace
of the Kellmans' existence

35:45.365 --> 35:46.731
and replaced it with yours.

35:46.766 --> 35:49.300
Now all I have to do is fill the
refrigerator with prune juice,

35:49.335 --> 35:50.268
and then I've got
to set up the--

35:50.303 --> 35:51.936
- Okay, get out.
- What?

35:51.971 --> 35:53.215
What do you mean get out?
I haven't set up the--

35:53.239 --> 35:54.350
She's pulling up.
She's here,

35:54.374 --> 35:55.551
and I don't want her
to see us together

35:55.575 --> 35:57.008
and get the wrong idea.

35:57.043 --> 36:00.077
- And exactly what idea is that?
- Okay, don't you understand?

36:00.305 --> 36:02.038
No woman could compete
with you,

36:02.074 --> 36:03.385
if she thought there was
even a chance

36:03.409 --> 36:04.608
of you and I being together.

36:04.642 --> 36:05.953
- Really?
- No, she blows you away.

36:05.977 --> 36:09.545
Now, get the hell out,
and use the service entrance.

36:13.345 --> 36:15.645
Tara, you're here.

36:15.681 --> 36:18.014
Oh, my God.

36:18.050 --> 36:20.917
Louis,
this place is wonderful.

36:20.953 --> 36:22.285
How long have you had it?

36:22.321 --> 36:25.188
Had it for generations.
Great-grandma Litt,

36:25.224 --> 36:28.558
she used to make wool
right over there by the fire.

36:28.594 --> 36:31.094
The natural light
is phenomenal.

36:31.129 --> 36:32.829
Phenomenal.

36:33.381 --> 36:35.848
And there's a wildness
to the landscape,

36:35.883 --> 36:38.183
an uninhibited energy.

36:38.219 --> 36:42.755
Wild.
Uninhibited.

36:42.790 --> 36:45.591
It's perfect for us, Louis.

36:47.762 --> 36:49.294
I'm glad you like it.

36:49.330 --> 36:51.764
I don't just like it.
I love it.

36:51.799 --> 36:53.632
Just like I love you.

36:53.667 --> 36:57.136
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:57.788 --> 36:59.087
Oh, Tara, I love you--

36:59.123 --> 37:01.323
- What?
- It.

37:01.358 --> 37:03.258
Your idea...what you were
talking about earlier.

37:03.293 --> 37:04.593
- Which idea?
- What happened?

37:04.628 --> 37:05.705
Louis, are you okay?
[door opens]

37:05.729 --> 37:08.130
What the hell
is going on here?

37:08.697 --> 37:09.763
Nothing's going on here.

37:09.798 --> 37:10.975
What the hell are you doing
in my house?

37:10.999 --> 37:12.766
- Your house?
- Louis, who are these people?

37:12.801 --> 37:14.568
These people are
the registered owners

37:14.603 --> 37:16.303
of this property.

37:16.338 --> 37:17.871
You mean the one you said
had been

37:17.906 --> 37:19.139
in your family
for generations?

37:19.174 --> 37:21.274
That's a lie.
We built this house ourselves,

37:21.310 --> 37:25.712
and until five minutes ago,
we were gonna sell it to him.

37:25.747 --> 37:27.380
Tara, I can explain.

37:27.416 --> 37:30.150
I don't need you to explain.
I've heard enough.

37:30.185 --> 37:33.220
Tara, wait.
Please.

37:33.864 --> 37:35.063
Tara, please wait.

37:35.098 --> 37:37.766
You know, I've heard
about people like you.

37:37.801 --> 37:39.479
You're trying to get free
design work out of me,

37:39.503 --> 37:42.070
so you can decide whether or not
you want to buy this house.

37:42.263 --> 37:43.374
That has nothing
to do with it.

37:43.398 --> 37:44.964
Really?
Because, first,

37:45.000 --> 37:46.077
you tried to get me
to work on this

37:46.101 --> 37:47.633
without even seeing the space.

37:47.669 --> 37:49.413
Then you lured me out here
under false pretenses.

37:49.437 --> 37:52.138
So why don't you tell me what,
exactly, is going on here?

37:52.173 --> 37:53.818
I lied to you about owning
a house in the Hamptons

37:53.842 --> 37:56.509
so I could spend time
with you.

37:57.101 --> 37:59.535
What?
Why--why would you do that?

37:59.571 --> 38:03.372
Because you are perfect,
and beautiful,

38:03.408 --> 38:06.509
and intelligent,
and talented,

38:06.544 --> 38:10.346
and so far out of my league.

38:10.381 --> 38:12.915
It was the only thing that I can
come up with to find the time

38:12.951 --> 38:15.751
I needed to make you
fall for me.

38:15.954 --> 38:17.887
You were willing to buy
and remodel

38:17.922 --> 38:21.591
an entire house to do that?
I was.

38:22.108 --> 38:26.911
That's the most romantic thing
I've ever heard.

38:26.946 --> 38:28.813
Really?

38:28.848 --> 38:32.950
Yeah. Yes, really.
[chuckles]

38:32.986 --> 38:36.053
Tara, would you like
to have dinner with me?

38:36.089 --> 38:38.489
I'd love to, Louis.

38:38.524 --> 38:41.726
- [chuckles]
- Yeah.

38:41.761 --> 38:44.695
<i>[soft music]</i>

38:48.601 --> 38:50.601
What are you working on?

38:51.110 --> 38:53.777
An engagement letter.

38:53.812 --> 38:54.878
You got a new client.

38:54.913 --> 38:57.714
I got us two new clients.

38:57.750 --> 38:59.850
So that's what you had
to do the other day.

38:59.885 --> 39:01.518
Well, something like that.

39:01.553 --> 39:04.888
The one I got the other day
led to the one I got today.

39:04.923 --> 39:06.490
That's great.

39:06.525 --> 39:09.493
Yeah, what's on your mind?

39:11.563 --> 39:12.907
I know you said that you'd
give me

39:12.931 --> 39:15.065
an hour of your time
later this week,

39:15.100 --> 39:17.167
but I need that hour tonight.

39:17.202 --> 39:18.769
Rachel, it's been a long day.

39:18.804 --> 39:20.181
Can we talk about this
in the morning?

39:20.205 --> 39:24.407
No, Jessica, we can't.

39:25.025 --> 39:29.361
Leonard Bailey's
execution date's been set,

39:29.396 --> 39:33.264
and I don't know how to tell
a man that he's going to die.

39:33.300 --> 39:36.201
<i>[dark music]</i>

39:36.236 --> 39:39.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:39.777 --> 39:41.088
You know,
I always knew that Jill and I

39:41.112 --> 39:43.112
were from two
different worlds.

39:45.349 --> 39:48.851
And she was a Sutter,
and I was just--

39:48.886 --> 39:49.963
A guy who was good
with numbers

39:49.987 --> 39:51.954
and didn't have much else?

39:54.191 --> 39:55.435
Figured it was only
a matter of time

39:55.459 --> 39:58.460
before she came to her senses,

39:58.496 --> 40:00.629
but she never did.

40:00.907 --> 40:04.175
Well, let me guess,
William never accepted it.

40:04.210 --> 40:06.043
No.

40:06.078 --> 40:08.779
So when he asked me
to develop that algorithm,

40:08.815 --> 40:12.817
I thought,
"This is my chance."

40:12.852 --> 40:16.620
And when I gave it to him,
he acted so proud.

40:16.656 --> 40:20.024
Started calling me
his genius son-in-law.

40:20.059 --> 40:21.837
But I was really just
the world's biggest sucker,

40:21.861 --> 40:24.028
because I let that son
of a bitch get one over on me,

40:24.063 --> 40:26.530
and I'll regret it
for the rest of my life.

40:28.868 --> 40:33.137
What if you could get
one over on him?

40:33.172 --> 40:36.173
What are you talking about?

40:37.610 --> 40:39.476
You said yourself,
they offered you a deal.

40:39.512 --> 40:41.445
I bet they'd still take it.

40:41.480 --> 40:44.515
No way. If I give them him,
they go after her.

40:44.550 --> 40:47.318
Not if you get them
to give Jill immunity first.

40:47.353 --> 40:48.452
- No.
- Kevin, you have to--

40:48.487 --> 40:51.155
It's too big a risk,

40:51.190 --> 40:52.601
and you're
my father-in-law's lawyer.

40:52.625 --> 40:53.635
You can't even be
saying this to me.

40:53.659 --> 40:54.692
I am nobody's lawyer.

40:54.727 --> 40:56.227
I am your friend,
and I am saying--

40:56.262 --> 40:58.662
Well, my answer's no,
and I want your word, right now,

40:58.698 --> 41:00.275
that you won't tell anyone
what I told you.

41:00.299 --> 41:02.010
- Kevin, please, you're not--
- Mike, I'm serious.

41:02.034 --> 41:05.936
No one can ever know anything
about what I told you.

41:05.972 --> 41:09.240
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:09.275 --> 41:11.709
You have my word.

41:11.744 --> 41:17.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:19.527 --> 41:23.396
Did I ever tell you
my mother was a teacher?

41:23.431 --> 41:26.732
First grade.

41:26.768 --> 41:28.668
Everybody always said she was
the best teacher

41:28.703 --> 41:30.937
their kid ever had.

41:30.972 --> 41:34.307
She loved it.

41:34.342 --> 41:37.877
She also always dreamed of
seeing Spain when she retired.

41:39.380 --> 41:42.315
That was supposed
to be six years ago,

41:42.350 --> 41:43.950
but then the state
teacher's pension fund

41:43.985 --> 41:48.387
decided to invest its money
with William Sutter.

41:51.659 --> 41:55.761
She died last year,
still working.

41:55.797 --> 41:57.107
And every year,
I tried to pay for her trip,

41:57.131 --> 41:59.165
but she just wouldn't let me.

41:59.200 --> 42:01.434
Sean, why are you
telling me this?

42:01.469 --> 42:03.769
Because a judge decided
to rule on your motion

42:03.805 --> 42:06.272
to dismiss after all.

42:06.307 --> 42:08.274
Which means
we're out of time,

42:08.309 --> 42:13.045
and you didn't just come here
to tell me about your mother.

42:13.081 --> 42:14.947
No.

42:14.983 --> 42:18.150
I came here to ask
for that trading program.

42:18.186 --> 42:21.354
<i>♪ ♪</i>

